 precariousness', in which new sets of risks and uncertainties have emerged. It adopts a multi-disciplinary approach, which is essential in developing a more subtle understanding of both the complex processes leading to, and the experience of, homelessness. Central to contemporary theory and practice is the enhancement of our understanding of how homelessness, disadvantage and social exclusion impact differently on various social groups. Homelessness provides a strong contribution to the academic debate, and is essential reading for students and researchers in a range of subject areas, including housing studies, social policy, socio-legal studies and public administration.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHomelessness. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Policy.2bisacsh1 aBeigulenko, Yana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCloke, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCowan, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFooks, Gary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForrest, Ray, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGilroy, Rose, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrison, Malcolm, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarvey, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHawes, Derek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKennett, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKennett, Patricia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMarsh, Alex, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarsh, Alex, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re